{
  "Which organelle contains the cell's genetic material and controls gene expression?": "",
  "Golgi apparatus": "",
  "Ribosome": "",
  "Nucleus": "",
  "Mitochondrion": "",
  "The nucleus is the membrane-bound organelle that houses the cell's chromosomal DNA. It is the site of DNA replication, transcription, and RNA processing in eukaryotic cells.": "",
  "Which organelle is the primary site of ATP production in eukaryotic cells?": "",
  "Endoplasmic reticulum": "",
  "Lysosome": "",
  "Chloroplast": "",
  "Mitochondria are the powerhouses of the cell, producing the majority of ATP through cellular respiration (Krebs cycle and oxidative phosphorylation on the inner mitochondrial membrane).": "",
  "What key structural feature distinguishes prokaryotic cells from eukaryotic cells?": "",
  "Prokaryotes lack a membrane-bound nucleus and other membrane-bound organelles": "",
  "Prokaryotes lack DNA": "",
  "Prokaryotes lack ribosomes": "",
  "Prokaryotes are always larger than eukaryotes": "",
  "Prokaryotic cells lack a true nucleus and membrane-bound organelles. Their DNA is located in a nucleoid region and they have 70S ribosomes, but no mitochondria, ER, or Golgi apparatus.": "",
  "Which organelle modifies, sorts, and packages proteins and lipids for transport?": "",
  "Smooth endoplasmic reticulum": "",
  "Peroxisome": "",
  "The Golgi apparatus (Golgi complex) receives proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum, further modifies them (glycosylation, phosphorylation), sorts them, and packages them into vesicles for delivery to their destinations.": "",
  "What is the primary function of ribosomes?": "",
  "Cell division": "",
  "Lipid metabolism": "",
  "DNA replication": "",
  "Protein synthesis (translation)": "",
  "Ribosomes are the molecular machines responsible for translating mRNA into polypeptide chains. They consist of a large and small subunit made of rRNA and proteins, with A, P, and E sites for tRNA binding.": "",
  "Which organelle contains hydrolytic enzymes for intracellular digestion?": "",
  "Smooth ER": "",
  "Lysosomes are membrane-bound vesicles containing hydrolytic enzymes (acid hydrolases) that function at an acidic pH (~5). They break down worn-out organelles, food particles, and foreign materials.": "",
  "What is the main difference between rough and smooth endoplasmic reticulum?": "",
  "Rough ER has ribosomes on its surface and is involved in protein synthesis; smooth ER lacks ribosomes and is involved in lipid synthesis and detoxification": "",
  "Smooth ER has ribosomes; rough ER does not": "",
  "There is no functional difference; the names refer only to appearance": "",
  "Rough ER is found only in animal cells; smooth ER is found only in plant cells": "",
  "Rough ER is studded with ribosomes that synthesize membrane-bound and secretory proteins. Smooth ER lacks ribosomes and functions in lipid synthesis, carbohydrate metabolism, calcium storage, and detoxification.": "",
  "Which structure is present in plant cells but absent in animal cells?": "",
  "Ribosomes": "",
  "Cell wall and central vacuole": "",
  "Mitochondria": "",
  "Cell membrane": "",
  "Plant cells have a rigid cellulose cell wall outside the cell membrane and a large central vacuole for water storage and turgor pressure. Animal cells lack both of these structures but have centrioles, which most plant cells lack.": "",
  "According to the endosymbiotic theory, which organelles were once free-living prokaryotes?": "",
  "Mitochondria and chloroplasts": "",
  "The nucleus and the nucleolus": "",
  "Golgi apparatus and lysosomes": "",
  "Ribosomes and the endoplasmic reticulum": "",
  "The endosymbiotic theory proposes that mitochondria evolved from aerobic bacteria and chloroplasts from photosynthetic cyanobacteria engulfed by ancestral eukaryotic cells. Evidence includes their double membranes, own circular DNA, and 70S ribosomes.": "",
  "What is the function of the cytoskeleton?": "",
  "It synthesizes lipids and hormones": "",
  "It stores genetic information": "",
  "It produces ATP for cellular energy": "",
  "It provides structural support, facilitates cell movement, and enables intracellular transport": "",
  "The cytoskeleton consists of microfilaments (actin), intermediate filaments, and microtubules (tubulin). It maintains cell shape, anchors organelles, enables cell motility, and serves as tracks for intracellular transport.": "",
  "What is the cell membrane (plasma membrane)?": "",
  "A selectively permeable phospholipid bilayer with embedded proteins that regulates the passage of materials into and out of the cell": "",
  "A layer of carbohydrates that protects the cell": "",
  "A rigid wall of cellulose that surrounds all cells": "",
  "A network of protein fibers inside the cell": "",
  "The cell membrane is a fluid phospholipid bilayer with embedded proteins (the fluid mosaic model). It is selectively permeable, controlling what enters and exits the cell through passive and active transport mechanisms.": "",
  "What does 'selectively permeable' mean?": "",
  "The membrane selects only water molecules to pass through": "",
  "The membrane allows all substances to pass through freely": "",
  "The membrane blocks all substances from crossing": "",
  "The membrane allows certain molecules to pass while restricting others based on size, charge, and polarity": "",
  "Selective permeability means the membrane allows some substances (small nonpolar molecules, water via aquaporins) to cross freely while restricting others (large molecules, ions), requiring specific transport proteins for their passage.": "",
  "What is the endoplasmic reticulum?": "",
  "The protein fibers that form the cytoskeleton, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "A network of membranous tubules and sacs (cisternae) extending from the nuclear envelope, involved in protein and lipid synthesis, modification, and transport": "",
  "A single membrane sac that stores water in plant cells, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "The outer boundary of the cell, which is consistent with how endoplasmic mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "The endoplasmic reticulum (ER) is an extensive network of membrane-enclosed tubules and flattened sacs connected to the nuclear envelope. Rough ER synthesizes proteins; smooth ER synthesizes lipids and detoxifies drugs.": "",
  "What does the term 'organelle' mean?": "",
  "A type of organ found only in multicellular organisms": "",
  "A specialized subcellular structure with a specific function, often enclosed by one or more membranes": "",
  "Any molecule found inside a cell": "",
  "The outer boundary of a prokaryotic cell": "",
  "An organelle is a distinct, often membrane-bound structure within a cell that performs specific functions. Examples include the nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts, ER, Golgi apparatus, and lysosomes.": "",
  "What is the endomembrane system?": "",
  "The network of mitochondria and chloroplasts in a cell when the interaction between endomembrane and system factors is taken into full account": "",
  "The outer cell membrane that surrounds the entire cell when the interaction between endomembrane and system factors is taken into full account": "",
  "The collection of internal membranes in eukaryotic cells that work together to modify, package, and transport proteins and lipids, including the nuclear envelope, ER, Golgi, lysosomes, and vesicles": "",
  "The system of microtubules that moves chromosomes during cell division, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "The endomembrane system includes the nuclear envelope, endoplasmic reticulum, Golgi apparatus, lysosomes, vacuoles, and plasma membrane. These components are connected through direct physical contact or vesicle trafficking.": "",
  "What does the term 'endosymbiosis' mean?": "",
  "The fusion of two gametes during fertilization, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual endosymbiosis mechanisms at work": "",
  "The movement of molecules from high to low concentration, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A relationship in which one organism lives inside the cells of another organism, with both partners benefiting; this explains the origin of mitochondria and chloroplasts": "",
  "The process by which cells divide into two daughter cells, based on conventional assumptions about endosymbiosis": "",
  "Endosymbiosis is a symbiotic relationship where one organism lives inside another. The endosymbiotic theory proposes that mitochondria and chloroplasts originated from prokaryotes engulfed by ancestral eukaryotic cells.": "",
  "What is the central vacuole?": "",
  "The central region of the nucleus where DNA is stored": "",
  "A small vesicle found in animal cells that stores waste": "",
  "A large membrane-bound compartment in plant cells that stores water, ions, and metabolites, and helps maintain turgor pressure": "",
  "A digestive organelle containing hydrolytic enzymes": "",
  "The central vacuole is a large, tonoplast-enclosed compartment occupying up to 90% of a mature plant cell's volume. It stores water, nutrients, and waste, and its turgor pressure provides structural support to the cell.": "",
  "What does the 'fluid mosaic model' describe?": "",
  "The arrangement of DNA in the nucleus due to the well-established relationship between fluid trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "The structure of the cell wall in plants when the interaction between fluid and mosaic factors is taken into full account": "",
  "The structure of the cell membrane as a dynamic, fluid phospholipid bilayer with a mosaic of embedded and peripheral proteins, cholesterol, and carbohydrates": "",
  "The pattern of ribosomes on the rough ER considering that the key variables involved tend to move in this direction together": "",
  "The fluid mosaic model, proposed by Singer and Nicolson in 1972, describes the cell membrane as a fluid phospholipid bilayer in which various proteins float like a mosaic. The membrane is dynamic, with components moving laterally.": "",
  "What is a chloroplast?": "",
  "An organelle found in plant cells and algae that carries out photosynthesis, converting light energy into chemical energy stored in glucose": "",
  "A membrane-bound vesicle that digests cellular waste": "",
  "A structure that packages proteins for secretion": "",
  "An organelle that breaks down glucose to produce ATP": "",
  "Chloroplasts are double-membrane organelles in plant cells and algae. They contain thylakoid membranes (site of light reactions) and stroma (site of the Calvin cycle) and have their own DNA, consistent with endosymbiotic origin.": "",
  "What does 'surface area-to-volume ratio' mean for cells?": "",
  "The percentage of a cell's volume occupied by the nucleus": "",
  "The speed at which a cell divides relative to its size": "",
  "The relationship between a cell's outer membrane area and its internal volume, which decreases as cells get larger and limits cell size": "",
  "The ratio of organelles to cytoplasm in a cell": "",
  "As a cell increases in size, its volume grows faster than its surface area (cubic vs. square relationship). This limits how efficiently materials can be exchanged across the membrane, constraining maximum cell size.": "",
  "A physician discovers that a patient's cells have defective lysosomes that cannot properly degrade glycogen. The patient develops Pompe disease, in which glycogen accumulates in cells, damaging muscles and organs. How does this illustrate the importance of lysosomal function?": "",
  "Lysosomes normally produce glycogen, so their malfunction stops glycogen production": "",
  "The glycogen accumulation is beneficial because it provides extra energy": "",
  "Lysosomes only function in immune cells, so muscle damage is unrelated": "",
  "Without functional acid hydrolases in lysosomes, cells cannot break down glycogen, causing toxic accumulation that disrupts normal cellular function and damages tissues": "",
  "Pompe disease is a lysosomal storage disorder caused by deficiency of acid alpha-glucosidase. Without this enzyme, glycogen accumulates in lysosomes, causing cellular damage particularly in cardiac and skeletal muscle.": "",
  "A cell biologist is studying a new single-celled organism under the electron microscope and observes a double-membraned nucleus, mitochondria, Golgi apparatus, and endoplasmic reticulum. The organism also has chloroplasts. What can she conclude about this organism's classification and metabolism?": "",
  "It is a prokaryote because it is single-celled": "",
  "It is a eukaryote capable of both photosynthesis (chloroplasts) and aerobic respiration (mitochondria), likely a photosynthetic protist or alga": "",
  "It is a virus because it is microscopic": "",
  "It is a bacterium with unusually complex internal membranes": "",
  "The presence of membrane-bound organelles (nucleus, mitochondria, ER, Golgi) identifies this as a eukaryote. Chloroplasts indicate it is photosynthetic. Many single-celled eukaryotes (algae, some protists) have both chloroplasts and mitochondria.": "",
  "A researcher studying antibiotic resistance notes that certain antibiotics target 70S ribosomes found in bacteria but not the 80S ribosomes of human cells. Why is this difference important for medicine?": "",
  "The structural difference between bacterial 70S and human 80S ribosomes allows antibiotics to selectively inhibit bacterial protein synthesis without harming human cells": "",
  "70S ribosomes produce different amino acids than 80S ribosomes": "",
  "Antibiotics must target 80S ribosomes to be effective against bacteria": "",
  "It is not important because all ribosomes function identically": "",
  "Antibiotics like tetracycline and streptomycin selectively bind bacterial 70S ribosomes, blocking protein synthesis. Because human cytoplasmic ribosomes are 80S with different structural features, these drugs do not affect human translation.": "",
  "A genetic engineer inserts a fluorescent marker gene into the rough ER signal sequence of a protein. She wants to track the protein's path from synthesis to secretion. In what order would the fluorescent protein travel through the cell?": "",
  "Rough ER → Golgi apparatus → transport vesicle → cell membrane (exocytosis)": "",
  "Smooth ER → lysosome → nucleus → cell membrane": "",
  "Free ribosome → cytoplasm → cell membrane": "",
  "Nucleus → mitochondria → cell membrane": "",
  "Secretory proteins follow the endomembrane pathway: they are synthesized on rough ER ribosomes, folded and modified in the ER lumen, transported to the Golgi for further modification and sorting, then packaged into vesicles that fuse with the plasma membrane for secretion.": "",
  "A patient with a mitochondrial disease has muscle weakness and fatigue because their mitochondria produce less ATP than normal. A geneticist discovers the mutation is in the mitochondrial DNA, not the nuclear DNA. The patient's mother has the same condition, but the father does not. Why is this disease inherited only from the mother?": "",
  "The mutation is on the X chromosome, which only mothers contribute": "",
  "Mitochondrial DNA is inherited exclusively from the egg (maternal inheritance) because sperm contribute virtually no mitochondria to the zygote": "",
  "Fathers have different types of mitochondria that cannot carry mutations": "",
  "Fathers never pass DNA to their children": "",
  "Mitochondria have their own circular DNA and are inherited maternally. The egg provides virtually all the cytoplasm (and mitochondria) to the zygote, while sperm contribute almost none. Thus, mitochondrial DNA mutations show maternal inheritance patterns.": "",
  "A plant biologist observes that when a plant wilts, it can recover if watered quickly. She explains this involves the central vacuole. What role does the central vacuole play in maintaining plant rigidity?": "",
  "When filled with water, the central vacuole generates turgor pressure that pushes the cell membrane against the rigid cell wall, keeping the plant upright; water loss causes the vacuole to shrink and the plant to wilt": "",
  "The central vacuole stores proteins that act as structural supports when the interaction between plant and central factors is taken into full account": "",
  "The central vacuole produces cellulose to strengthen the cell wall given that prevailing plant conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "The central vacuole contracts like a muscle to hold the plant upright given that prevailing plant conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "The central vacuole absorbs water by osmosis, expanding and pressing the cell membrane against the cell wall (turgor pressure). This pressure provides structural support. When water is lost, turgor pressure drops and the plant wilts (plasmolysis).": "",
  "A toxicologist studying liver cells notes that chronic alcohol exposure leads to a dramatic increase in smooth endoplasmic reticulum (SER) in hepatocytes. What functional relationship explains this observation?": "",
  "SER produces alcohol in liver cells given that prevailing alcohol conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "SER expansion is caused by protein synthesis in response to alcohol within the broader context of alcohol analysis": "",
  "Smooth ER contains enzymes (such as cytochrome P450) that detoxify drugs and alcohol; chronic exposure induces proliferation of SER to increase detoxification capacity": "",
  "SER stores alcohol for later use as cellular fuel in most scenarios involving alcohol factors": "",
  "The smooth ER in liver cells houses cytochrome P450 enzymes that metabolize drugs and toxins, including alcohol. Chronic alcohol exposure upregulates these enzymes, causing SER proliferation to increase the cell's detoxification capacity.": "",
  "A microbiologist argues that mitochondria were once free-living bacteria based on several lines of evidence. Which of the following is NOT valid evidence for the endosymbiotic origin of mitochondria?": "",
  "Mitochondria have double membranes, with the inner membrane resembling a bacterial plasma membrane": "",
  "Mitochondria reproduce by binary fission similar to bacteria": "",
  "Mitochondria have their own circular DNA similar to bacterial genomes": "",
  "Mitochondria contain 80S ribosomes identical to those in the host cell's cytoplasm": "",
  "Mitochondria contain 70S ribosomes (like bacteria), NOT 80S ribosomes (which are in the eukaryotic cytoplasm). The 70S ribosomes are key evidence for endosymbiosis, as they match bacterial ribosome size.": "",
  "A cancer researcher observes that rapidly dividing tumor cells are significantly smaller than normal cells of the same tissue type. Using the concept of surface area-to-volume ratio, why might smaller cell size be advantageous for rapidly dividing cells?": "",
  "Smaller cells are harder for the immune system to detect, particularly in the context of cells": "",
  "Smaller cells have a higher surface area-to-volume ratio, enabling more efficient nutrient uptake and waste removal to support the rapid metabolic demands of frequent division": "",
  "Cell size has no effect on division rate given that prevailing cells conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "Smaller cells have less DNA, so they can divide faster according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Smaller cells have a greater surface area relative to their volume, allowing more efficient exchange of nutrients and waste across the membrane. This supports the high metabolic rate needed for rapid cell division in tumors.": "",
  "A genetic disorder called I-cell disease results from a defective enzyme in the Golgi apparatus that normally adds mannose-6-phosphate tags to lysosomal enzymes. Without these tags, hydrolytic enzymes are secreted outside the cell instead of being directed to lysosomes. What cellular consequence would you predict?": "",
  "Lysosomes would contain too many enzymes and digest the entire cell": "",
  "Cells would produce excess ATP from the misdirected enzymes": "",
  "Lysosomes would lack their digestive enzymes, causing undigested substrates to accumulate inside cells and resulting in cellular dysfunction across multiple organ systems": "",
  "The Golgi would stop producing vesicles entirely": "",
  "Mannose-6-phosphate is the sorting signal that directs lysosomal enzymes from the Golgi to lysosomes. Without this tag, enzymes are mistakenly secreted. Empty lysosomes cannot digest waste, leading to inclusion bodies of undigested material (hence 'I-cell' disease).": ""
}